article.description: Kevin Garnett scored 29 points and Anthony Peeler added 26, including seven 3-pointers, as the Minnesota Timberwolves beat the Seattle SuperSonics 111-106 on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Peeler's seven 3-pointers too much for Sonics

images.name: Peeler, Anthony 020109 inline
images.caption: Anthony Peeler scorched the Sonics with a career-high seven 3-pointers.

article.linkText: Wolves' Peeler stalks Sonics with career-high seven 3's
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Anthony Peeler made the Seattle SuperSonics pay for leaving him open. Peeler scored 26 points, shooting 7-for-9 from 3-point range, to lead the Minnesota Timberwolves to a 111-106 victory over Seattle on Wednesday night. Peeler's seven shots from the behind the arc were the most by a Minnesota player this year. His seventh 3-pointer put Minnesota ahead 86-73 with 8:53 to go in the fourth quarter. "We've been waiting for stuff like this all season, to get open shots like that," Peeler said. "We're a team that rotates the ball and that's what makes us effective." With the Seattle defense trying to clamp down on Kevin Garnett on the inside and Gary Payton paying most of his attention to Wally Szcerbiak on the perimeter, the Wolves were able to swing the ball out to Peeler. "He was on fire," Garnett said. "He was the spark we needed coming off the bench. "They're a team that likes to trap and play the passing lanes, so it forced us to pass and share the ball. When we get the ball moving like that, you get easy shots." Garnett led the Wolves with 29 points and 10 rebounds. Chauncey Billups and Szczerbiak each had 16 points. "When he's shooting like that, you've got to run every play in the book to get him off," Billups said of Peeler. Payton had 25 points for Seattle, but only attempted three field goals in the fourth quarter. Seattle stayed within striking distance thanks to Vin Baker's inside play. Baker constantly found himself in good position in the post and was able to overmatch Minnesota's smaller frontcourt. Baker had 23 points and Rashard Lewis led Seattle with 30. Lewis hit a 3-pointer with 15.4 seconds left in the game to pull the Sonics within 108-104. After Peeler missed the second of two free-throws, Payton drove the lane untouched and made it 109-106. But Szczerbiak's two free throws padded the Wolves' lead with 4.4 seconds to go. "We hit a big shot and they'd come down and hit a big shot. There's nothing we can do," Lewis said. Billups started his ninth game in place of the injured Terrell Brandon. His highlight of the game was a long-range jumper with 4:00 left to give the Wolves a 96-86 lead. Peeler threw the inbound pass cross-court to Billups, whose feet never hit the ground before getting the shot off just before the shot clock buzzer. "Billups' shot was unbelievable," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "It gave them momentum. I think it drains you mentally." Billups said the shot was typical of how the big plays went Minnesota's way. "It felt good, but it was just lucky," he said. The Timberwolves overcame a slow start plagued by turnovers and led by as many as 12 points in the first half. Peeler fueled a 17-6 run with back-to-back 3-pointers. Felipe Lopez capped off the run with a dunk off a steal to give Minnesota a 48-36 lead with 5:35 left in the half. The Timberwolves led 54-48 at halftime.

Game notes
Wednesday night's game was Payton's 900th of his 11-year career. He's Seattle's all-time leader in points, assists, steals and minutes played. Payton trails Fred Brown (963) in games played. ... The Sonics are now 13-1 when scoring more than 100 points. ... Minnesota hasn't lost to Seattle at home since March 1998.
